1. Boolean Values (true, false) 
  - are basically little on-off switches
  - example below:   illustrates how you can use a parameter to create an on/off switch


function test (myCondition) {
  if (myCondition) {
     return "It was true";
  }
  return "It was false";
}
test(true);    // returns "It was true"
test(false);  // returns "It was false"


//END Boolean on off switch example 


2. Equality Operator (==) V.S. Strict Equality (===)
  - Equality operator will work to being compared to a string vs a number (e.g. 1 == "1" is true)
  - Strict Equality will strictly only work if similar types (e.g. 1 === "1" is false)



3. Typeof
  - typeof <variable> can help determine what the variable type is(eg string/number/boolean)



4. Switch statements

   ```javascript
   switch(num) {  
   
    case value1:    
   
    	statement1;     
   
   	break;
   
    case value2:    
   
   	statement2;
   
   	break; 
   
   ...   
   
   case valueN:
   
   	statementN;	
   
   	break; }
   
   ```

   * Case values are tested with strict equality **===**

   * In case statements you may not be able to specify the values, so you can add the **default** statement (similar to else statement in if/else if)

   * ```javascript
     switch(val) {
       case 1:
       case 2:
       case 3:
         result = "1, 2, or 3";
         break;
       case 4:
         result = "4 alone";
     }
     ```

